newsitem.title: USA: NYMEX natgas called down slightly with cash, OTC.
newsitem.headline: NYMEX natgas called down slightly with cash, OTC.

text.p: NYMEX Henry Hub natgas futures were expected to open down slightly Friday, in line with reports of softer physical and over-the-counter prices, industry sources said.
June over-the-counter trades were reported at $2.18 and $2.19, with the bid and ask range now $2.17-2.19.
On ACCESS, June waffled between $2.193 and $2.21, last trading down 0.3 cent at $2.193. Other months finished narrowly mixed.
In the morning cash, Henry Hub was quoted between $2.16 and $2.20, down from Thursday's range of $2.20-2.23.
NYMEX will be closed Monday for U.S. Memorial Day.
While some expected a pullback ahead of the holiday weekend, few expected the market to break down, noting good support just below current levels.
"There's no weather but the board still won't break down," said one Midwest trader.
Forecasts for next week call for normal to slightly below-normal weather for the upper two-thirds of the nation, with some above-normal temperatures expected in Texas and parts of the Southeast.

Technical traders agreed there was little reason for a breakout. June support and resistance were still seen at $2.15 and $2.30, respectively. Major buying was likely at the $2.05 double bottom, with good selling expected at the contract high of $2.43.

In Thursday's cash, Gulf Coast swing prices were steady to up slightly Thursday to the high-teens. Midcon pipes were little changed in the low-$2s. New York city gate gas also held relatively steady in the mid-$2.40s.

Planned work on Mobil's Mary Ann gas processing plant in Coden, Ala., has cut the plant's total processing capacity of 380-390 mmcfd. About 120 mmcfd should be back by early next week, with the balance due back in three weeks.
